<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE1416CCA81E9B2FEE1209D" bold="true" box="[199,339,222,248]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">References:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE1416CCB1CE9B3FE6F209C" author="Hemp, C." box="[346,477,223,249]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474" refId="ref16956" refString="Hemp, C. (2021) A Field Guide to the Bushcrickets, Wetas and Raspy Crickets of Tanzania and Kenya. Senckenberg Gesellschaft fur Naturforschung, Frankfurt, 451 pp." type="book" year="2021">Hemp 2021</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE1416CCA81E86EFD282100" blockId="23.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE1416CCA81E86EFED02179" bold="true" box="[199,354,258,284]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Tegmina (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE1416CCB9CE86FFDAF2178" box="[474,541,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1741,1765]" captionTargetBox="[161,1415,290,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-72@5.[151,1436,273,1718]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Left male tegmina of Acanthoplus discoidalis (CH8946), Acanthoproctus cervinus (CH8947), Hetrodes pupus (CHelb8948), Enyaliopsis bloyeti (CH8853), E. carolinus (CH8625), E. ephippiatus (CH7737), E. jennae (damaged; CH8267), Gymnoproctus rammei (CH8763), Eugasteroides loricatus (CH7352), Spalacomimus stettinenesis, S. talpa (CH7354), S. verruciferus (CH7188). Scale 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392715/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), stridulatory file (
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE1416CC8A9E86FFCF02178" box="[751,834,259,285]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,332,356]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Body dimensions and characteristics of stridulatory files in Hetrodini" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101" pageId="23" pageNumber="474" tableUuid="0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101">Table 1</tableCitation>
), and spectrum of the song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE1416CCEC5E86FFB74217B" box="[1155,1222,259,286]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1287,1311]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,201,1247]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Power spectra of male calling songs in Hetrodini species" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392725/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) do not show large differences to the typical 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE1416CCBE8E84BFDAB2124" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[430,537,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
pattern. The calling song consists of a long, uninterrupted trill (song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFE1416CCF55E84BFAF12124" box="[1299,1347,295,321]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">type</typeStatus>
A) with a SRR of about 28 Hz (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE1416CCBDBE827FDB32100" box="[413,513,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1322,1346]" captionTargetBox="[156,1433,260,1291]" captionTargetId="figure-48@14.[151,1436,237,1299]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Eugaster, Eugasteroides and Spalacomimus (figures of S. liberianus based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Eugaster guyoni, B Eugaster spinulosa, C Eugasteroides loricatus, D Spalacomimus liberianus, E Spalacomimus magnus, F Spalacomimus stettinensis, G Spalacomimus talpa, H Spalacomimus verruciferus, I Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392739" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392739/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">Fig. 10E</figureCitation>
; see 
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE1416CC87EE827FD3F2100" box="[568,653,331,357]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,236,476,501]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. Song characteristics of Hetrodini species (for song type see Fig. 5 and text)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190" pageId="23" pageNumber="474" tableUuid="0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE1416CCA81E802FD0921C8" blockId="23.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE1416CCA81E802FE8F21ED" bold="true" box="[199,317,366,392]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">Genitalia.</emphasis>
The titillator is relatively large and massive with short basal parts and a slightly bifurcate tip (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE1416CCF29E803FF7821C8" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1046,1070]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,272,1023]" captionTargetId="figure-69@15.[151,1436,272,1023]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Titillators in the genus Spalacomimus. A S. magnus (Gulwe), B S. stettinensis (Lambo Estate), C S. stettinensis (neotype), D S. talpa (Lembeni), E S. verruciferus (Lake Chala), F S. spec. near verruciferus (Lossogonoi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392741/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
). The lateral sclerites are weakly developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE1416CCA81E8DBFEE3227C" blockId="23.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">
Chro 
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE1416CCAB9E8DBFEC721B4" bold="true" box="[255,373,439,465]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474">mosomes:</emphasis>
2n = 17 (16 + X0), FN = 28; pairs 1–5 meta/submetacentric, 6–8 acrocentric, X chromosome submetacentric (
<specimenCount id="41F9FD5DFFE1416CCB17E8B7FE1F2193" box="[337,429,475,502]" pageId="23" pageNumber="474" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
); thin C-positive paracentromeric bands in all chromosomes and an interstitial one on the pair 2 (
